<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-15T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-15T23:00:00-05:00" n="256" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d256">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/2008: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-16T00:00:00-04:00">August 16,
                                1937—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>237. From Hornbeck.<note n="51" xml:id="d256fn51">Stanley K. Hornbeck,
                                Adviser on Political Relations.</note> Your 495, August 16, 4 p.m.
                            Paragraphs 1, 3 and all: you have my sympathy.</p>
                        <p>Paragraphs 2, 4, 5, 6: I am sure action will be approved.</p>
                        <p>Paragraph 7, second sentence: Steps have been initiated to provide funds
                            to cover emergencies.</p>
                        <p>I understand that Navy Department has sent message to Commander in Chief
                            which I trust will be good news to both Commander in Chief and you.
                            [Hornbeck.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>